<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d53b7c5f9b5f5557b9082face9b632a0?s=50"></div><header><strong>[Pitch] Adding a Self type name shortcut for static member access</strong> from <string>Dave Abrahams</string> &lt;dabrahams at apple.com&gt;<p>April  6, 2016 at 09:00:00am</p></header><div class="content"><p>on Wed Apr 06 2016, Brent Royal-Gordon &lt;swift-evolution at swift.org&gt; wrote:<br></p><p>&gt;&gt; Alternatively, why is it ‘dynamicType’ and not just ‘type’?<br>&gt;<br>&gt; I suspect this has something to do with the 27 methods in various OS X<br>&gt; frameworks named `type`. (To be fair, 17 of those are in WebKit&#39;s DOM<br>&gt; classes.)<br></p><p>Really, no.  It&#39;s because something&#39;s static type is a useful<br>distinction from its dynamic type, and this clarifies which one you&#39;re getting.<br></p><p>&gt; What I&#39;m less sure about is why it&#39;s not a free function<br>&gt; instead. Other than the `dynamicType` and `self` pseudo-properties,<br>&gt; I&#39;m not aware of any members which are present on all types. We might<br>&gt; be better off making `dynamicType` a free `typeof(_:)` function (or<br>&gt; should it be `type(of:)`? are `sizeof` and friends changing?) and<br>&gt; `self` a free `identity(_:)` function; these would make them<br>&gt; non-magical parts of the language, which would be kind of neat.<br></p><p>-- <br>Dave<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
